	<text>
		<body xml:lang="en">
			<div>

	<pb n="0001" facs="liv_002670_0001"/><!--pb/@n='1'-->
<lb/><p><handShift new="#CGR"/>Copy of original historical 
<lb/><hi rend="underline">letter from D<hi rend="sup underline">r</hi> David Livingstone</hi></p>
<lb/><p><placeName>Cassange</placeName></p>
<lb/><p>14<hi rend="sup underline">th</hi> Feby 1855 </p>
<lb/><p>My dear <persName>M<hi rend="sup underline">r</hi> Gabriel</persName></p>
<lb/><p>Along with this I enclose the map 
<lb/>&amp; letter for <persName>Sir R. Murchison</persName><reg>.</reg>
<lb/>In opening it you will find it easy 
<lb/>if you will let it stand an hour or two 
<lb/>in a towel on which you sprinkled 
<lb/>some water previously. </p>
<lb/><p>The same process will enable you to 
<lb/>fold it again with facility </p>
<lb/><p>Please when you write to <persName>Lie<hi rend="sup underline">ut</hi>
<lb/><choice><sic>Bendingfeld</sic><corr>Bedingfeld</corr></choice></persName> present my compliments 
<lb/>on his escape. </p>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent">Fancy the natives in 1855 of the "new" 
<lb/>"earth", &amp; no more sea, digging up my 
<lb/>fossil manuscripts &amp; as much puzzled 
<lb/>to tell the situation of <placeName>Angola</placeName> as the 
<lb/>Commentators have been with the 
<lb/>whereabouts of the <placeName>Garden of Eden.</placeName> 
<lb/>As you are a lawyer in embryo 
<lb/>(pardon) I suppose the decision that 
<lb/>a person born out of <placeName>England</placeName> is an 
<lb/>"alien"- will change your views a 
<lb/>little, I believe it was given in a 
<lb/>case of copyright. </p>

	<pb n="0002" facs="liv_002670_0002"/><!--pb/@n='2'-->
<lb/><p><hi rend="underline">2.</hi><hi rend="underline">re Gabriel</hi></p>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent">English parents don't now produce 
<lb/>English children</p>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent">Mine are therefore niggers - "moleques"- 
<lb/>in fact for they were born in <placeName>Africa</placeName>
<lb/>Excuse the hotch potch note </p>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent">Believe me ever most 
<lb/>affectionately yours </p>
<lb/><p>(sd.) <persName>David Livingstone </persName></p>
<lb/><p>Copied from original 
<lb/><persName>C. G. Reeve</persName>
<lb/>London 
<lb/>Feby 1938 </p>
			
